					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/snakeoilsage" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1364996); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1364996&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610183403" alt="SnakeoilSage" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1364996)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/snakeoilsage" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1364996); return false;" >SnakeoilSage</a></span> <span class="odate time_1380205122 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">26 Sep 2013 14:18</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1858986">
									

<p>The inspiration came to me as I was playing &quot;A Machine for Pigs.&quot; I was disappointed with the direction it took. Instead, I started playing out my own plot: &quot;What if they're not on earth anymore?&quot; I thought it would be cool if the big revelation was that they were in some kind of limbo, and the father had teleported the house there so they wouldn't have to live in Victorian London because reasons.</p>
<p>So yes, &quot;A Machine for Pigs&quot; is in there, as well as &quot;The Dark Descent,&quot; &quot;Eternal Darkness: Sanity's Requiem,&quot; and even some of Stephen King's &quot;The Mist.&quot;</p>

							</div>

								
					
