		<div class="post" id="post-1861947">
		<div class="long">
			<div class="head">
									<div class="options">
						<a href="javascript:;" onclick="togglePostFold(event,1861947)" class="btn btn-default btn-small btn-sm">Fold</a>
					</div>
								<div class="title" id="post-title-1861947">
																		
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/wishun" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1204404); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1204404&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610183403" alt="wishun" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1204404)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/wishun" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1204404); return false;" >wishun</a></span> <span class="odate time_1380654051 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">01 Oct 2013 19:00</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1861947">
									

<p>I think I'm going to go with an all-of-the-above head canon on this one.</p>
<p>By sheer chance some of the workers were not there when the machine was turned on. The &quot;miraculous&quot; disappearance of the manor and their co-workers drove out any lingering doubts, creating a solid cadre of true believers that formed the seed of a new religion. As worm-touched machines trickled back into base reality, they incorporated them into the growing theology. Today we call them the CotBG.</p>
<p>The main function of the trap itself was to channel the corrupt energy of the worm into the creation of a nearly-alive, self-operating, ever-growing mechanical labyrinth. This &quot;Pipe Nightmare&quot; served as an endless oubliette, a further layer of mechanistic chains on the worm. But the defiling nature of that energy gave the beast ways to reach out from within its prison and <em>twist</em>. It took only a few days to create the infection we call 217 and release it to punish the lesser peons who had a hand in building the trap. It took years of limbo-time before it was able to exert enough influence to convert pieces of the randomly-generating outer prison into a self-sustaining &quot;Factory&quot;. With a portion of the constraining energies thus diverted into the creation of reality-defying consumer goods, the worm was able to partially free itself. It was still bound up in the core device, but it at least managed to impinge itself on the prime material plane. Dragging the engine along like steel jaws on the mangled paw of a bear. The violence of that breakout left holes. Holes thru which the Factory could &quot;ship&quot; its &quot;merchandise&quot; and the pipes could blindly grope, probing ever further in search of their lost inmate. Some portions of the prison, more broken than the rest, fell thru those holes. Wherever there is an inexplicable machine, an artillery installation firing infinite mice, or a derelict ship that thinks it is alive, that is a snippet of the prison.</p>
<p>The worm had not neglected vengeance on the man who engineered the snare. For all it strained to subvert the jail, it poured equal measure of hate into grinding his soul between the increasingly corrupted gears of the core. If such a being can be said to regret, it regretted not being able to bring the victim along out of limbo for additional torments. That broken, maddened old man would spread the worm's corruption yet further, reaching out from the industrial limbo-complex to inflict a portion of his own suffering on anyone unfortunate enough to catch his attention. Forever dripping the unclean combination of worm ichor and tainted oil that had soaked his very soul.</p>

							</div>

								
					
